# gen189 (basic-chat cat.0): NON-LINGUISTIC input recognition. parrot0 now makes
# a structural distinction BEFORE the reasoning core — "is this language at all?"
# — and redirects at the channel level instead of the topic-level "I don't
# understand that yet." This is a character-structure classifier, NOT a phrasebook
# of these strings: it generalizes to any punctuation-only / bare-number /
# keyboard-mash input (PRINCIPLES.md: honest redirect, never a feigned answer).

# Punctuation / symbols only.
> ?
< That's just punctuation, not words — what would you like to ask?
> !
< That's just punctuation, not words — what would you like to ask?
> !@#$%^&*()
< That's just punctuation, not words — what would you like to ask?

# A bare number with no operation to perform (>=4 digits).
> 1234567890
< That's just the number 1234567890 with nothing to do — what would you like me to do with it?

# Keyboard-mash letters: a long consonant run, then a single repeated character.
> asdfghjkl
< That doesn't look like words to me — did a key get stuck? I'm here when you'd like to ask something.
> aaaaaaaaaa
< That doesn't look like words to me — did a key get stuck? I'm here when you'd like to ask something.

# Guards: real language must still pass through, not be mistaken for noise. A
# structured dot/dash code is named by the symbolic recognizer (not called
# noise); an ordinary greeting reaches the social register untouched.
> ... --- ...
< That looks like Morse code.
> hello
< Hi there!